330. As a rnle, the antique worshipper stood up. But the worshippers of Isis, agreeably to their habits (cp. note on uera, 24), were provided with seats. These benches (so in the temple of Isis at Pompeii) or cathedrae (Mart. 2, 14, 8) were set before the altar (ante focos, Ovid, Pont. 1,1,52)

where the occupante could contemplate the image of the goddess when the sanctuary was opened (stares). Delia is for the time to become a devotee of Isis, taking her place among the regular worshippers, lino tecta, ‘dressed in linen,’ the wearing of which at all times was incumbent on the priests, cp. Herod. 2, 37, and often.
